<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[96,1533,323,427]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[96,256,324,352]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Etymology.</emphasis>
The proposed name is for the late Dr. G. J. Phanuel (Professor, Dept. of Zoology, MCC) who worked extensively on the spiders of Madras in the early 1960s. His work has been of great significance for later workers. The name is masculine in gender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[96,1537,473,727]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[96,247,473,502]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small spiders characterized by short, very high cephalothorax, high and reduced thoracic region; abdomen round, nearly spherical. Leg III distinctly longer. Two RTAs (compared to usually two RTAs, sometimes with one RTA in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1884" box="[564,690,547,577]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Aelurillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[564,690,547,577]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Aelurillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and two peaks, separated by a V or U shaped slit in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1876" box="[1413,1517,547,577]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Phlegra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1413,1517,547,577]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Phlegra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Simon" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1901" box="[274,488,584,615]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Langona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[274,391,584,614]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Langona</emphasis>
Simon
</taxonomicName>
in lacking a bunch of stiff hairs projecting from the base near RTA. Differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Simon" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1886" box="[176,461,621,652]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Stenaelurillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[176,358,621,652]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Stenaelurillus</emphasis>
Simon
</taxonomicName>
due to the absence of an anterior tegular apophysis. Embolus longer and thinner than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1886" box="[323,505,659,690]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Stenaelurillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[323,505,659,690]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Stenaelurillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Epigynum highly sclerotized, convex surface, with copulatory openings postero-laterally (whereas these are antero-median in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1884" box="[839,965,697,727]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Aelurillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[839,965,697,727]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Aelurillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or hidden in circular grooves in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1876" box="[1413,1517,697,727]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Phlegra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1413,1517,697,727]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Phlegra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[96,1535,773,1102]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[96,276,773,802]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Description.</emphasis>
Spiders with small body (
<quantity box="[635,747,773,802]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3-4 mm</quantity>
), carapace short and very high, short longitudinal fovea in a rounded, pit-like shallow depression in the centre just behind PLE line midway (
<figureCitation box="[1216,1325,811,840]" captionStart="Figures 26-29" captionStartId="7.[242,334,1952,1976]" captionTargetBox="[246,1388,1049,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-311@7.[246,1388,1048,1943]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figures 26-29. Male Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 26, Dorsal view. 27, Lateral view. 28-29, Front" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092987" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092987/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 26</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1338,1377,811,840]" captionStart="Figures 32-37" captionStartId="8.[288,379,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[288,1344,767,1925]" captionTargetId="figure-49@8.[288,1344,767,1925]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figures 32-37. Female Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 32, Dorsal view. 33, Abdomen. 34-36, Front view. 37, Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092991/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">32</figureCitation>
). Carapace widest at beginning of posterior slope; posterior slope very steep. PME closer to PLE than ALE. Clypeus vertical, moderately high (
<figureCitation box="[464,578,886,915]" captionStart="Figures 26-29" captionStartId="7.[242,334,1952,1976]" captionTargetBox="[246,1388,1049,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-311@7.[246,1388,1048,1943]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figures 26-29. Male Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 26, Dorsal view. 27, Lateral view. 28-29, Front" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092987" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092987/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 28</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[593,633,886,915]" captionStart="Figures 32-37" captionStartId="8.[288,379,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[288,1344,767,1925]" captionTargetId="figure-49@8.[288,1344,767,1925]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figures 32-37. Female Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 32, Dorsal view. 33, Abdomen. 34-36, Front view. 37, Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092991/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">36</figureCitation>
). Male chelicerae without any tooth. Leg III longer than leg IV (
<figureCitation box="[106,216,923,952]" captionStart="Figures 26-29" captionStartId="7.[242,334,1952,1976]" captionTargetBox="[246,1388,1049,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-311@7.[246,1388,1048,1943]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figures 26-29. Male Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 26, Dorsal view. 27, Lateral view. 28-29, Front" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092987" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092987/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 27</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[230,269,923,952]" captionStart="Figures 32-37" captionStartId="8.[288,379,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[288,1344,767,1925]" captionTargetId="figure-49@8.[288,1344,767,1925]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figures 32-37. Female Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 32, Dorsal view. 33, Abdomen. 34-36, Front view. 37, Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092991/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">37</figureCitation>
). Abdomen small, rounded with pairs of white spots arranged in the median, lighter lateral regions seen on females (
<figureCitation box="[447,558,961,990]" captionStart="Figures 26-29" captionStartId="7.[242,334,1952,1976]" captionTargetBox="[246,1388,1049,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-311@7.[246,1388,1048,1943]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figures 26-29. Male Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 26, Dorsal view. 27, Lateral view. 28-29, Front" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092987" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092987/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 26</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[572,611,961,990]" captionStart="Figures 32-37" captionStartId="8.[288,379,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[288,1344,767,1925]" captionTargetId="figure-49@8.[288,1344,767,1925]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figures 32-37. Female Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 32, Dorsal view. 33, Abdomen. 34-36, Front view. 37, Lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092991/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">33</figureCitation>
). Male palp with enlarged bulbus, tegulum leathery, embolus thin, two RTA, one long and bent at tip which is inconspicuous, other conspicuous, short and thick (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 38-46" captionStartId="9.[287,379,1861,1885]" captionTargetBox="[288,1345,165,1851]" captionTargetId="figure-63@9.[289,1345,672,1228]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figures 38-46. Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 38, Left male palp, ventral view. 39, Left male" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092993" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092993/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 38, 39</figureCitation>
). Epigynum highly sclerotized, copulatory openings laterally placed apart, with meandering copulatory ducts (
<figureCitation box="[341,550,1073,1102]" captionStart="Figures 38-46" captionStartId="9.[287,379,1861,1885]" captionTargetBox="[288,1345,165,1851]" captionTargetId="figure-63@9.[289,1345,672,1228]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figures 38-46. Phanuelus gladstone sp.nov. 38, Left male palp, ventral view. 39, Left male" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5092993" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5092993/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 40, 43, 44</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[96,1534,1147,1214]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[96,239,1147,1176]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Affinities.</emphasis>
Species show clear affinity to subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[869,1028,1148,1177]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Aelurillinae">Aelurillinae</taxonomicName>
in genital structures and general morphology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
